gland"},"nl":{"Abt 1285–":"circa 1285–Overleden","1285–Female":"1285–Overleden","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1311–1388":"1311–1388","–1350":"–1350","1270–1311":"1270–1311","Abt 1285":"circa 1285","Abt 1311":"circa 1311","1311":"1311","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1285–":"about 1285–Deceased","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1311–1388":"1311–1388","–1350":"–1350","1270–1311":"1270–1311","Abt 1285":"about 1285","Abt 1311":"about 1311","1311":"1311","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cave","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in East Yorkshire called Cave, apparently from a river name derived from Old English <i>cāf</i> ‘swift’.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Norman and Picard Old French <i>cauf</i> (from Latin <i>calvus</i>) ‘bald’.","French: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a cave, from Old French <i>cave</i> ‘cave’, ‘cellar’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i>, a derivative of <i>cavus</i> ‘hollow’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Cave was born about 1285, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Joan Of The Channel Islands. She married Roger Dakeney in 1310, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"Abt 1285–":"umbes 1285–Surnud","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1311–1388":"1311–1388","–1350":"–1350","1270–1311":"1270–1311","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","Abt 1311":"umbes 1311","1311":"1311","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1285–":"noin 1285–Kuollut","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1311–1388":"1311–1388","–1350":"–1350","1270–1311":"1270–1311","Abt 1285":"noin 1285","Abt 1311":"noin 1311","1311":"1311","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1285–":"environ 1285–Décédée","1285–Female":"1285–Décédée","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1311–1388":"1311–1388","–1350":"–1350","1270–1311":"1270–1311","Abt 1285":"environ 1285","Abt 1311":"environ 1311","1311":"1311","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Cave est née environ 1285, à Buckinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fille de Joan Of The Channel Islands. Elle a épousé Roger Dakeney en 1310, à Buckinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 2 filles."},"de":{"Abt 1285–":"um 1285–Verstorben","128